ners in Christian Spain and Portugal maintained slaves at home, frequently captives taken in wars and sea raids, and exported their slave systems to colonies across the Atlantic.Slavery in Medieval and Early Modern Iberia provides a magisterial survey of the many forms of bound labor in Iberia from ancient times to the decline of slavery in the eighteenth century. William D. Phillips, Jr., examines the pecuniary and legal terms of slavery from purchase to manumission. He pays particular attention to the conditions of life for the enslaved, which, in a religiously diverse society, differed greatly for Muslims and Christians as well as for men and women. This sweeping narrative will become the definitive account of slavery in a place and period that deeply influenced the forms of forced servitude that shaped the New World.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSlaveryzIberian PeninsulaxHistoryy16th century. 0aSlaveryzIberian PeninsulaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSlaveszIberian PeninsulaxHistoryy16th century. 0aSlaveszIberian PeninsulaxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aWorld History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package World Historyz978311041347208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220917440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812209174423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812209174.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041347-2  Penn Press eBook Package World History  a978-3-11-